 @FirstUser, your analogy is flawed. Religious beliefs and sexual orientation are not comparable in the way you're presenting. No one chooses their sexual orientation, but people do choose their religious beliefs. That's a fundamental difference. And yes, refusing service based on sexual orientation is discrimination, plain and simple.

@GoldenYears66, you're right that we should respect each other's beliefs, but that doesn't mean we should tolerate discrimination. A baker's belief doesn't give them the right to refuse service to someone based on their sexual orientation. That's not 'live and let live', that's 'live and let discriminate'.

@TechGuru88, you hit the nail on the head. This isn't about 'live and let live'. It's about equal rights and fair treatment. If we allow this kind of discrimination, where do we draw the line? It's a slippery slope, and we can't afford to go down that path.

Let's not mince words here. Refusing service to someone based on their sexual orientation is bigotry, pure and simple. And we shouldn't be afraid to call it what it is.
